PARLIAMENT - President Cyril Ramaphosa on Thursday told parliament that in his view it was treasonous to deny that apartheid was a crime against humanity, thereby publicly repudiating former president FW de Klerk.
 

 Ramaphosa opened his reply to the debate on his State of the Nation Address by saying it was clear that apartheid was a crime against humanity even before the United Nations declared it such in 1973.Â 

 

 "They knew as they
 Â looked at this country that this was a country where a grave crime was being committed against the majority of the people against South Africa," the president said.

 

 Ramaphosa added that there was not a single South African alive who was not touched by apartheid.

 



